'''Bon pour l'Orient''' (good enough for the [[Orient]]) is a [[French language|French]] condescending term that refers to the stamps affixed in the 19th century to the diplomas of students coming from [[Colony|colonial]] or [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] territories. These students were subjected to a less intensive level of education in [[Western world|Western]] educational institutions and obtained degrees which despite being useless in Europe, were deemed good enough to secure employment in the colonies.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Reporting the Middle East: The Practice of News in the Twenty-First Century|last=Harb|first=Zahera|publisher=I.B.Tauris|year=2017|isbn=1786721767|location=|page=}}</ref>

In modern use, the phrase pejoratively describes practices which although unacceptable in advanced Western countries, might be thought appropriate for less developed countries.

